{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7ebf9895-e333-4b94-9c53-e4339f13437d","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is a managed application-level exception — it's not related to CLR activation. CLR activation logs only cover the process of **loading the .NET runtime itself** (e.g., picking the right CLR version, resolving mscoree.dll). By the time your app throws a `NullReferenceException`, activation has already succeeded.\n\n**To diagnose your crash, you'd want to look at:**\n\n1. **The exception stack trace** — it will point to the exact line with the null dereference.\n2. **Application event logs** or crash dumps, not CLR activation logs.\n\nDo you have a stack trace, crash dump, or source code you'd like me to look at?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"651781f4-db6c-467f-910b-982427222eca","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, I need to think about whether this is the right tool. The user has a NullReferenceException, which is a managed exception - not typically a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs are about the process of loading the CLR runtime itself (choosing the right runtime version, loading mscoree.dll, etc.), not about debugging application-level exceptions like NullReferenceException.\n\n\nI should clarify this distinction for the user and explain why CLR activation logs won't help with their NullReferenceException, then suggest more appropriate debugging approaches instead.","outputTokens":380,"requestId":"6406:C174F:14A86FE:1811201:69EC173D"},"id":"3ed59d44-21c8-4f35-ac8a-f37ec7a41792","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:22:15.645Z","parentId":"c37fe454-9d8a-4a20-9a42-458c0cf9801